<article>
    <h1>Cel&#xAD;e&#xAD;brate with lo&#xAD;cal flavours</h1>
    <h2>What bet&#xAD;ter way to mark Na&#xAD;tional Day than to feast on Sin&#xAD;ga&#xAD;porean fare in novel forms?</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200802/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-08-02"><time>2020-08-02</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE FOOD &amp; DRINK</span>
        - <span role="byline">Eu&#xAD;nice Quek Food Cor&#xAD;re&#xAD;spon&#xAD;dent&#xD;&#xA;eu&#xAD;niceq@sph.com.sg&#xD;&#xA;&#x2022;&#xD;&#xA;Fol&#xAD;low Straits Times Food on Face&#xAD;book and In&#xAD;sta&#xAD;gram @strait&#xAD;stimes&#xAD;food</span>
    </section>

    <p>Food pa­tri­o­tism is at an all-time high in the lead-up to the na­tion’s 55th birth­day next Sun­day.</p>
    <p>Fast-food chains have been quick to launch Na­tional Day-themed of­fer­ings boast­ing unique Sin­ga­porean flavours since last month.</p>
    <p>KFC de­buted its Flossy Crunch Chicken, crispy fried chicken coated in curry and lo­cal spices and topped with spicy-sweet chicken floss. Re­turn­ing favourites in­clude Texas Chicken’s salted egg fried chicken, avail­able till Aug 26, and Burger King’s ren­dang beef burger, avail­able till Aug 31.</p>
    <p>Restau­rant chefs and bak­eries are also rolling out the red and white car­pet for sweet treats, tak­ing in­spi­ra­tion from nostalgic favourites such as pan­dan, ban­dung, con­densed milk or chilli crab.</p>
    <p>It is time to cel­e­brate as a foodie na­tion. Here are five items to get you in the mood.</p>

